                <head>No. 946<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">Editorial Note</hi>
                </head>
                <p>On September 2, <persName corresp="#p_RAYNORGH1">G. Hayden Raynor</persName> met
                    with Ambassador <persName corresp="#p_WRONGH1">Wrong</persName> to discuss plans
                    for an informal and unannounced visit by <persName corresp="#p_PEARSONLBM1"
                        >Lester Pearson</persName> to Washington September 4–5. He was expected to
                    arrive mid-afternoon, hold brief meetings with appropriate persons, have dinner
                    with a small group including Secretary <persName corresp="#p_ACHESOND1"
                        >Acheson</persName> at the Embassy or Chancery, and leave Washington after
                    lunch on September <pb facs="0946" n="2036" xml:id="pg_2036"/> 5. The Ambassador
                    said <persName corresp="#p_PEARSONLBM1">Pearson</persName> wanted to discuss
                        <gloss target="#t_NATO1">NATO</gloss> questions, the United Nations General
                    Assembly’s handling of the Korean question, and the status of the St. <persName
                        corresp="#p_VASSLC1">Lawrence</persName> Seaway and Power Project.
                    (Memorandum of conversation, by <persName corresp="#p_RAYNORGH1"
                        >Raynor</persName>, September 2, 1952; 742.13/9–252) Records of a <persName
                        corresp="#p_PEARSONLBM1">Pearson</persName> visit and discussions of
                    September 2–4 have not been found in Department of State files.</p>
            </div>
